# c books

# goal: learn c to ~k&r fluency, then write it correctly/safely.
# see why-learn-c for the case, and c-to-rust-rewrite for what comes after.


# best book to actually LEARN c from today
# C Programming: A Modern Approach, 2nd Edition
# - K. N. King
# - beginner-friendly, thorough, excellent exercises, covers C99
# - the usual "one book to learn c" pick. start here if learning fresh.


# modern, correct, current-standard c
# Modern C
# - Jens Gustedt
# - covers C11 / C17 / C23, very current
# - free legal PDF online. read after the basics.


# secure / correct c, by a standards-committee expert
# Effective C, 2nd Edition (2024)
# - Robert Seacord (No Starch)
# - modern standards + heavy focus on undefined behavior and security
# - good "now write it correctly" follow-up


# the classic — own it, but not as your first teacher
# The C Programming Language, 2nd Edition (1988)
# - Brian Kernighan & Dennis Ritchie ("K&R")
# - iconic, concise, beautiful prose; great reference
# - dated: C89, terse, assumes you can already program, some idioms now
#   considered bad practice (gets, implicit int). read as a supplement.


# systems depth (not strictly a c book)
# Computer Systems: A Programmer's Perspective ("CS:APP")
# - Bryant & O'Hallaron
# - best book for WHY c behaves as it does at the machine level


# the path
# - learning fresh:  K. N. King (main) + Modern C (free, brings you current)
# - K&R alongside for prose / history
# - Effective C once the basics are solid, to write safe modern c
